===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

In the oracle bone script, it was an {{liushu|ic|nocap=1}}: 2 or 4 {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|屮||grass}} or even {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|木||tree}} + {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|日||sun}} + {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|月||moon}} – the sun rising above the ground while the waning moon is still in the sky – the morning.

In the bronze script, it was a compound of {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|𠦝}} and a pictograph of a river ({{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|川}} or {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|水}}) – this was possibly an original form for {{och-l|潮|gloss=tide}}. The river glyph may be a corruption of {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|月}} due to association with tides or diurnal events. {{zh-ref|Chi (2010)}} considers such forms to be {{liushu|psc|nocap=1|adj=1}}, where {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|𠦝}} is the abbreviated form of the phonetic {{och-l|朝}}. In the some late Western Zhou forms, {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|𠦝}} was corrupted into a form resembling {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|車}}.

According to {{w|Guo Moruo}}, in the stone drum inscriptions ({{lw|zh|石鼓文}}, likely from the {{w|Spring and Autumn period}}) {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|㫃}} was added (attached to {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|車}}), and the river glyph was replaced with {{och-l|舟}}, which was interpreted as the phonetic component; the small seal script might have inherited from this form. ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' interpreted the fused components of {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|𠦝}} and {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|㫃}} as a semantic component {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|倝||dawn}}. However, the accuracy of identification has been questioned; the character was a heavily weathered one in which the {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|㫃}} identification was probably spurious and likely influenced by the ''{{w|Shuowen}}''. Meanwhile, the {{lang|zh|舟}} component on the right remained somewhat legible.<ref>{{cite-journal|zh|title=zh:郭沫若《石鼓文研究》摹本及释文辨正|author=zh:徐宝贵|journal={{lang|zh|考古学报}}|date=2007-07-15|issue=2007-03|pages=313–338}}</ref>

The {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|舟}} component remained in the {{w|bamboo and wooden slips}} of the {{w|Warring States period}} (see the table). In the clerical script since the {{w|Han dynasty}}, {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|舟}} had been reverted to {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|月}}; it is unclear whether this was a remnant from {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|月}} in the oracle bone script or a corruption of {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|舟}} (as in {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|朕}} < {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|𦩎}} and many other characters). The current form is essentially inherited from the clerical script.

===Etymology===
“Morning” > “perform the morning ceremony” > “to go/come to court; to have an audience”. Derivative: {{och-l|潮|gloss=morning tide}}.

Perhaps related to {{cog|th|เพรา||morning}} ({{zh-ref|Manomaivibool, 1975}}).

